DUAL MODEL DETECTION + TRACKING PIPELINE — LOGIC DOCUMENTATION
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════


───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
1. OVERVIEW
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Two models run on each frame:

  - General model (YOLO26m): detects standard COCO classes —
    person (0), car (2), motorcycle (3), bus (5), truck (7),
    traffic light (9), stop sign (11)

  - Finetuned model: detects domain-specific classes —
    soldier, barrier

The finetuned model only runs when the general model detects a
"trigger label" (soldier or barrier). Otherwise only general model
results are returned. This avoids running two full inference passes
on every frame when it is not needed.


───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
2. INFERENCE PARAMETERS
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Each model has its own inference parameters because they were
trained differently and serve different purposes.

General model (YOLO26m):
  conf=0.25       low threshold to catch everything, filter later
  imgsz=640       standard resolution
  iou=N/A         YOLO26 is NMS-free, iou parameter has no effect

Finetuned model:
  conf=0.35       slightly higher — domain-specific model should
                  be more certain before reporting a detection
  imgsz=640       match training resolution
  iou=0.5         NMS threshold if using YOLO11-based finetuned,
                  lower than default (0.7) because soldiers and
                  barriers can appear close together and a high
                  NMS threshold risks merging two nearby objects
                  into one box before reconciliation runs

NOTE on iou= parameter vs reconciliation IoU:
  These are two completely different things.
  - iou= in ultralytics: Non-Maximum Suppression threshold.
    Used INSIDE the model to remove duplicate detections of the
    same object by the same model. Has nothing to do with our code.
  - IoU in reconciliation: our geometric check to decide if a
    general model box and a finetuned model box are detecting
    the same physical object. Computed AFTER inference in our code.


───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
3. CONFLICT DETECTION — WHEN DO TWO BOXES MEAN THE SAME OBJECT?
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

After both models run, we compare every finetuned box against
every general box. For each pair we ask: same object or different?

We use three geometric signals in order:


SIGNAL 1 — IoU (Intersection over Union)
─────────────────────────────────────────
         intersection
IoU  =  ─────────────
             union

Symmetric — does not care which box is bigger. Measures how much
two boxes overlap relative to their combined area.

  0.0       no overlap at all
  0.1–0.2   touching or small edge overlap
  0.3–0.4   meaningful overlap, probably related
  0.5+      heavily overlapping, likely same object
  0.7+      almost identical boxes, definitely same object

IoU is the strongest signal. If it is above threshold we declare
a conflict immediately without checking further.

Limitation: if two boxes are very different sizes (e.g. a small
cone box inside a large truck box), the union is large and IoU
is dragged down even if they are detecting the same object.
This is why we need IoF as a second signal.


SIGNAL 2 — IoF (Intersection over Foreground), symmetric
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
         intersection
IoF  =  ─────────────────
         one box's area

Unlike IoU, IoF measures what fraction of ONE specific box is
covered by the other. We compute it in both directions and take
the maximum:

  iof_over_fin = intersection / finetuned box area
  iof_over_gen = intersection / general box area
  symmetric IoF = max(iof_over_fin, iof_over_gen)

Taking the max means we catch containment regardless of which
box is bigger:

  - Finetuned box inside general box:
    iof_over_fin is high, iof_over_gen is low → max is high ✓

  - General box inside finetuned box:
    iof_over_fin is low, iof_over_gen is high → max is high ✓

  - Adjacent boxes, small edge overlap:
    both are low → max is low ✓

This catches cases IoU misses — e.g. the rear end of a truck
detected as a barrier. The barrier box is small and mostly inside
the truck box, so IoF is high even though IoU is low.

IoF is only used as a conflict signal when combined with the
center check (see below) because IoF alone can be fooled by
a real barrier that clips the edge of a truck box.


SIGNAL 3 — Center inside check
────────────────────────────────
Check whether the center of the finetuned box lies inside the
general box.

This is the tiebreaker for medium IoF values. A real adjacent
object (barrier next to truck) will have its center outside the
truck box even if the edges touch. A false detection (truck rear
end called a barrier) will have its center inside the truck box.

  Real barrier next to truck:
    barrier center is to the right, outside truck box → no conflict ✓

  Truck rear end called barrier:
    barrier center is inside the truck box → conflict ✓


FULL CONFLICT DECISION TREE
────────────────────────────

  IoU >= threshold?
      YES → same object, apply strategy
      NO
        IoF >= threshold AND center inside?
            YES → containment confirmed, apply strategy
            NO  → different objects, keep both


───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
4. CONFLICT RULES — THRESHOLDS AND WHY
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Rules are defined as:
  (finetuned_label, general_label) → (iou_thresh, iof_thresh, strategy)


soldier vs person  →  (0.5, 0.7, always_finetuned)
───────────────────────────────────────────────────
A soldier is a person. Their bounding boxes should be nearly
identical — same height, same width, same position. IoU can
easily reach 0.8+ for the same physical body.

IoU threshold 0.5: set well below the expected 0.8+ so we catch
all real conflicts. Still high enough that a soldier standing
NEXT TO a civilian (IoU ~0.1) is not treated as a conflict.

IoF threshold 0.7: strict because soldier and person boxes should
be nearly the same size. If IoF is below 0.7 the boxes are too
different in size to be the same person.

Strategy always_finetuned: a soldier IS a person. The finetuned
label is more specific, not contradictory. Confidence is
irrelevant — even a 40% confident soldier detection beats a 95%
confident person detection because the label carries more
information regardless of score.


barrier vs any general label  →  (0.3, 0.6, highest_conf)
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Barrier covers a wide range of physical shapes — red/white
barriers, cones, checkpoints, long thin barriers, jersey blocks.
Each shape produces a very different bounding box. Even when the
general model and finetuned model detect the same barrier object,
their boxes may not align well.

IoU threshold 0.3: lower than soldier because barrier boxes are
shape-inconsistent. A cone next to a motorcycle and a wide
barrier next to a truck will have low IoU even when detected as
the same object. Setting threshold too high would miss these.
0.3 is meaningful overlap for differently shaped objects.

IoF threshold 0.6: 60% containment required. Strict enough to
avoid false conflicts from edge clips between genuinely separate
objects, but low enough to catch containment of differently
shaped boxes.

Strategy highest_conf: barrier and vehicle are genuinely
different object types — unlike soldier/person they are not the
same thing. A truck could genuinely be there. A barrier could
genuinely be there. Whichever model is more confident is more
likely to be correct.


Edge case — truck driving behind a long/wide barrier:
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
A partially visible truck behind a wide barrier produces a small
truck box sitting inside a large barrier box. IoF will be high
(most of the truck box is covered by the barrier box). Center
check will likely pass too (truck center inside barrier box).

This triggers a conflict and highest_conf decides the winner.
This is acceptable — you cannot geometrically distinguish
"truck misdetected as barrier" from "real truck behind real
barrier." Confidence is the only available signal.

If the barrier model is confident and the truck model is not
(partially occluded truck = lower confidence) → barrier wins.
If the truck model is confident → truck wins, barrier is kept
as a separate detection only if its center is outside the truck.


───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
5. STRATEGIES — HOW CONFLICTS ARE RESOLVED
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Once a conflict is confirmed by geometry, a strategy function
is called to decide which detection to suppress.

Strategies are defined as a dict of functions in strategies.py:

  STRATEGIES = {
      "always_finetuned": _strategy_always_finetuned,
      "highest_conf":     _strategy_highest_conf,
  }

always_finetuned:
  Suppresses the general model detection unconditionally.
  The finetuned label always wins regardless of confidence score.
  Used for soldier vs person.

highest_conf:
  Compares confidence scores of both detections.
  The detection with the higher score survives.
  The lower confidence detection is suppressed.
  Used for barrier vs all general labels.

Using a dict means:
  - All valid strategies are visible in one place
  - A typo in CONFLICT_RULES raises an error immediately
  - Adding a new strategy requires only a new function and one
    line in the dict — reconcile() never needs to change


───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
6. TRACKING PROBLEMS AND SOLUTIONS
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

PROBLEM 1 — Two trackers, two ID systems
──────────────────────────────────────────
If each model runs its own tracker, the same physical person
gets two different track IDs:

  general model tracker:   person  → ID 1
  finetuned model tracker: soldier → ID 7   (same person)

When reconciliation suppresses the person box, ID 1 disappears
and ID 7 takes over. The tracker thinks the person left and a
new object appeared. If finetuned does not trigger next frame,
ID 7 disappears and ID 1 comes back — another false new object.

Solution: run one single tracker on the merged output after
reconciliation. One physical object → one box → one ID.
The tracker never sees duplicate boxes for the same object.


PROBLEM 2 — Label flipping between frames
───────────────────────────────────────────
The finetuned model only runs when a trigger is detected. A
soldier might be labelled correctly in frame 1 but if confidence
drops slightly and finetuned does not run in frame 2, the same
track gets relabelled as person. Frame 3 it is soldier again:

  frame 1: soldier ✓  (finetuned triggered, conf=0.72)
  frame 2: person  ✗  (finetuned did not trigger, conf=0.28)
  frame 3: soldier ✓  (finetuned triggered, conf=0.68)

The track ID is stable but the label keeps flipping.

Solution: label memory. Once a track is confidently assigned
a finetuned label (soldier or barrier), lock that label to the
track ID. Even if finetuned does not run next frame, the label
stays as soldier until the track dies and is removed from memory.


PROBLEM 3 — Label memory sticks to wrong track after ID switch
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
If two people walk close together and the tracker confuses them
(a common failure under occlusion), the soldier label memory
could get assigned to the wrong track ID:

  person A → ID 1 (civilian)
  person B → ID 2 (soldier, label locked)

  they cross, tracker switches IDs:
  person A → ID 2  (now wrongly inherits soldier label)
  person B → ID 1  (loses soldier label)

This is worse than no label memory — the wrong person is
permanently labelled as a soldier.

Solution: only lock the label when confidence is high (≥ 0.6).
A high confidence soldier detection is much less likely to be
a tracker ID switch artefact. Low confidence detections that
would flip the label are ignored — the existing locked label
is kept instead.


HOW THE THREE SOLUTIONS WORK TOGETHER
───────────────────────────────────────
  single tracker           solves problem 1 (no duplicate IDs)
  label memory             solves problem 2 (no label flipping)
  confidence threshold     solves problem 3 (memory not misassigned)

Each depends on the previous:
  - Label memory only makes sense if there is a single ID per object
  - Confidence threshold only matters if you have label memory


───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
7. FILE STRUCTURE
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  constants.py    pure data — COCO_NAMES, COCO_CLASSES,
                  TRIGGER_LABELS, CONFLICT_RULES, thresholds.
                  No functions, no logic. Could be written as JSON.

  strategies.py   strategy functions and STRATEGIES dict.
                  All conflict resolution logic lives here.
                  No knowledge of models or geometry.

  geometry.py     box_iof_symmetric(), center_inside(),
                  is_conflict(). Pure box math. No side effects.
                  No knowledge of models or strategies.

  utils.py        get_video_fps(), get_video_metadata(),
                  extract_estimated_frames(). Generic helpers
                  with no knowledge of detection logic.

  detector.py     get_detections(), reconcile(), run_general(),
                  run_finetuned(), detect(). Imports from all
                  four files above. Main entry point.

Dependency flow (no circular imports):
  constants.py  ←── no internal imports
  strategies.py ←── no internal imports
  geometry.py   ←── no internal imports
  utils.py      ←── no internal imports
  detector.py   ←── imports from all four


───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
8. FULL FRAME LOOP SUMMARY
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

For each frame:

  1. Run general model
  2. Check if any trigger labels detected (soldier, barrier)
  3. If yes → run finetuned model
     If no  → return general detections as-is
  4. Reconcile: compare every (finetuned box, general box) pair
       - Check IoU → if above threshold, conflict confirmed
       - Else check IoF + center → if both above threshold, conflict
       - Else keep both boxes
       - On conflict: apply strategy (always_finetuned / highest_conf)
  5. Feed merged detections into single tracker
  6. Apply label memory to stabilise labels across frames
  7. Clean up memory for tracks that have died
